.th ERRPRNT VII 6-September-1979
.sh NAME
errprnt \*- print error message and exit
.sh SYNOPSIS
.ft B
char *argv0 0; /* copy 0th parameter \*- program's name */
.br
main(argc, argv)
.br
char **argv;
.br
{
.br
	argv0 = argv[0];
.br
	...
.s3
errprnt(comstr, arg);
.br
char *comstr;
.ft R
.sh DESCRIPTION
.it Errprnt
is a subroutine that printf's the calling program's name
and a user supplied command string that may use
an optional second argument.
.it Errprnt
sends to the diagnostic file 2 that is normally the user's tty.
.s3
The calling program's name is supplied through the commom variable
.bd argv0
that should be set equal to the calling programs argument 0
by the main routine.
The user supplied command string
.bd comstr
may use one single word optional second parameter
.bd arg
such as a string pointer or an integer.
After printing
.bd comstr,
.it errprnt
prints a carriage return and exits back to the operating system
using return code 1.
.s3
Versions are available for both the standard printf or
the portable C library version.
.sh DIAGNOSTICS
If argv0 is not defined in the main program, ld(I) complains.
